  "body": "## Preamble\r\n\r\n    VIP: 823\r\n    Title: Use only wei_value for wei parameters\r\n    Author: Ben Kaufman \r\n    Type: Standard Track\r\n    Status: Draft\r\n    Created: 2018-05-16\r\n    Requires: #653\r\n\r\n\r\n## Simple Summary\r\nChange all low-level functions using wei to require explicit conversion to ``wei_value``.\r\nMake ``wei_value`` be ``uint256`` to prevent negative values.\r\n\r\n## Abstract\r\nThis VIP is based upon VIP #653.\r\nCurrently, all wei is managed by ``int128``, but all low-level functions with wei parameters like ``raw_call`` and ``send`` expect to receive ``int128``. I propose changing this so they will accept only ``wei_value``.\r\n\r\n## Motivation\r\nThe current situation has a few flaws:\r\n1. This code will compile\r\n```\r\n@public\r\ndef __init__(dest: address):\r\n    send(dest, -1)\r\n```\r\n2. ``wei_value`` can be a negative number (you shall never have negative wei)\r\n```\r\n@public\r\ndef __init__(dest: address):\r\n    send(dest, as_wei_value(-1, \"wei\"))\r\n```\r\n3. Low-level functions expect to receive a number and not ``wei_value``, this means it's implicitly treated as wei. I believe all usage in wei should be explicitly in ``wei_value``.\r\n\r\n## Specification\r\nThe technical specification should describe the syntax and semantics of any new feature. The specification should be detailed enough to allow any developer to implement the functionality\r\n\r\n## Backwards Compatibility\r\nThis requires changing low-level functions as well as implementing VIP #653 which will cause backwards incompatibility.\r\n\r\n## Copyright\r\nCopyright and related rights waived via [CC0](https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/)\r\n\r\n\r\n#### Cute Animal Picture\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10667901/40097115-08b463ec-58dd-11e8-839d-585d44674063.png)\r\n",
